TITLE: Child Process Shell Execution and Kill Limitations in Node.js
DESCRIPTION: This example shows a limitation of the kill() method when dealing with nested processes. When a process is spawned within a shell, killing the parent process may not terminate child processes on Linux systems.
SOURCE: https://github.com/caido/doc-developer/blob/main/src/reference/modules/llrt/child_process.md#2025-04-20_snippet_21

LANGUAGE: javascript
CODE:
```
'use strict';
const { spawn } = require('child_process');

const subprocess = spawn(
  'sh',
  [
    '-c',
    `node -e "setInterval(() => {
      console.log(process.pid, 'is alive')
    }, 500);"`
  ], {
    stdio: ['inherit', 'inherit', 'inherit']
  }
);

setTimeout(() => {
  subprocess.kill(); // Does not terminate the Node.js process in the shell.
}, 2000);
```
